<PageHero
  kicker="2022 Distinguished Lectureship"
  title="Dorothea Frede"
  subtitle="“Aristotle’s ‘Political Architect’ and the City of His Prayers”"
  image="/assets/images/parthenon_night.jpg"
/>

<section class="section two-col">
  <div><h2>The 2022 lecture</h2></div>
  <div>
    <p><strong>Dorothea Frede</strong>, Professor Emerita of Philosophy at Hamburg University.</p>
    <p><strong>Date:</strong> Friday, December 16, 2022 · 1:00pm–3:00pm EDT.</p>
    <p><strong>Commentators:</strong> Melissa Lane and James Warren.</p>
    <p>This event was held via Zoom.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section two-col">
  <div><h2>Abstract</h2></div>
  <div>
    <p>
      At the beginning of the <em>Nicomachean Ethics</em>, Aristotle invokes the need
      for a master-science that determines the good human life in a community by
      providing for its order and laws.
    </p>
    <p>
      Frede examines legislation, its role in Aristotle’s ethical and political thought,
      and its compatibility with Aristotle’s apparent preference for a theoretical form of life.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section two-col">
  <div><h2>Participants</h2></div>
  <div>
    <p>
      Dorothea Frede is an internationally renowned scholar of Ancient Greek philosophy,
      with influential work on Plato, Aristotle, Hellenistic philosophy, and Heidegger.
    </p>
    <p>
      Melissa Lane is Class of 1943 Professor of Politics at Princeton University.
    </p>
    <p>
      James Warren is Professor of Ancient Philosophy at the University of Cambridge.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>

